try point. I'm settling on a cleaner architecture: the runtime gets a `RestartWithCommand` method that commits the container state to a temporary image and spins up a fresh container from it, preserving all filesystem changes while running the new command. For host-based resumption, the engine replays completed step results and picks up execution from the resume point, using the `-c` flag for prompt steps. I'm also thinking through what the `--resume-from` flag should do at the agent binary level.\n\nThe agent would parse the workflow, load cached outputs from previous steps, and run the engine in resume mode starting from the specified step, with prompt steps using the `-c` flag to continue conversations. Now I'm mapping out the implementation order: add the `ResumeRun` RPC, regenerate protobuf, implement `Exec` on the runtime, add the engine's `Resume` method, wire up agent CLI support, update the prompt adapter, implement server-side handling, and add the CLI command. Actually, I'm reconsidering the container approach—instead of `docker commit`, I should explore a simpler method for restarting a stopped container.\n\nFor a stopped container, I could copy updated files back in and use `docker commit` to snapshot the filesystem into a new image, then launch a fresh container from that with the resume command. But wait, I'm overcomplicating this. Let me refocus on what the requirements actually ask for: script steps should rerun fresh with all prior outputs available, and prompt steps should resume the conversation using the `-c` flag rather than starting over.\n\nThe key insight is that the container persists even after failure, so I just need to handle three cases differently—for scripts, copy in any updated files; for prompts, use the resume flag; for workflows, re-dispatch with prior outputs. I'll add a method to the container runtime that handles this restart logic cleanly. I'm realizing the cleanest approach is to write a resume marker file into the stopped container via `docker cp`, copy any updated scripts, then restart it—the agent checks for this marker on startup and enters resume mode from the specified step, avoiding the need for container commits or new images.\n\nNow I'm thinking through the agent-side implementation: it needs to check for the resume marker file at startup, read the step name, and configure the engine to replay completed steps before resuming from that point, using the `-c` flag for any prompt steps. I should also add a `ResumeRun` RPC with a request that includes the run ID and target step name.\n\nFor the engine, I need a method that accepts the workflow, resume point, and completed steps, then skips everything before that point and replays their results before continuing normally. The prompt adapter will need a flag to switch into resume mode, which changes how it formats prompts. And for the Docker runtime, I realize `docker cp` actually works on stopped containers, so I can write the updated files directly without needing new interface changes.\n\nWait, but the container runtime interface only exposes `CopyFrom`, not `CopyTo`. I need to add that method to handle copying files into the container before resuming. Let me add a `CopyTo` method to the ContainerRuntime interface rather than embedding the logic in the gRPC server.\n\nNow I'm planning the implementation order: first the proto definitions and generated code, then adding `CopyTo` to the runtime interface, implementing the Resume method in the engine, setting up the agent runner for resume mode, updating the prompt adapter to handle the retry context, building the gRPC handler, adding the CLI command, and finally writing tests.\n\nFor the engine's resume logic, I need to think through how to handle the step execution flow carefully—skipping completed steps while replaying their results so downstream wiring still fires, then starting actual execution from the resume point.\n\nImplementing the Resume method... I'm checking if a step has