{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01SfFPE7Wo2rqmg2xuGV8VZ8","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The generated protobuf code is complex and tied to a raw descriptor. Modifying it manually would be error-prone and fragile. Let me use the metadata approach instead - passing resume info via gRPC metadata headers, similar to how `follow` and `limit` are passed in StreamLogs. This avoids touching the protobuf files entirely.\n\nBut I realize there's an even better approach: I'll use the RunWorkflow RPC itself, just adding gRPC metadata for resume. The server side checks for the metadata and enters resume mode.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach is: bypass gRPC entirely for this new RPC by defining a simple handler using the low-level gRPC API. \n\nI keep overcomplicating this. The simplest solution is to just use the existing RunWorkflow RPC with metadata headers - I'll call GetStatus to fetch the run details first, then invoke RunWorkflow with the resume metadata attached.\n\nBut wait, GetStatus doesn't actually return the project directory, so I need to figure out how the CLI would know where to point to. Let me check what fields are actually in the GetStatusResponse...\n\nLooking at the proto definition, it has the run_id, workflow_name, and state, but no project_dir. The server has access to the full run record though, so it could handle the resume logic entirely server-side. That means the CLI just needs to send the run_id and step name as metadata headers, and let the server look up everything else from the stored run. The tricky part is that RunWorkflow expects a WorkflowName parameter, so I might need to use a sentinel value or find another way to signal resume mode without requiring that field.\n\nSetting up the metadata headers...\n\nI'm implementing the server-side handler to check for resume mode in the context and route to the appropriate logic, keeping the existing RunWorkflow path intact for normal requests.\n\nThe 30-second timeout works fine since RunWorkflow returns immediately regardless of whether it's a new run or resuming an existing one. Now I need to map out the full implementation plan across the proto definitions, engine layer, adapters, runners, gRPC server, CLI, and tests.\n\nFor the container resume flow, I'm thinking through how to inject the resume marker file into a stopped container—the server writes it to a temp location, uses `docker cp` to transfer it into the container, syncs any updated scripts or overrides, then restarts the container with its original command. The agent detects the resume file on startup and continues from where it left off, with logs streaming from the restarted container just like a fresh run.\n\nThe challenge is that `docker start` on an exited container will show both the original run's logs and the new output mixed together, which makes tracking confusing. A cleaner approach would be to use `docker commit` to snapshot the stopped container into a temporary image, then spin up a fresh container from that image with the same environment variables and mounts—this gives us clean logs and proper isolation. The tradeoff is that I'd need to modify the `Start()` method to handle creating a container from a committed image rather than from scratch, but that's more manageable than dealing with interleaved logs.\n\nI'm thinking through a `RestartWithCommand` method that would handle this workflow: commit the old container to a temp image, create a new container from that image with the updated command, start it, and return the new container ID along with the output stream. The Docker commands would be straightforward—commit, create with the same working directory and new command, then start. Though I'm realizing that `docker commit` only preserves the filesystem state, not the environment variables or other container config, so I'd need to reapply those when creating the new container.\n\nActually, I can simplify this significantly. Since the agent only needs the workspace files and the API key can be reinjected, I can just commit the container to a temp image and then use the existing `runtime.Start()` method with a custom command for resuming. The `ContainerConfig.Cmd` field already supports this, so I can pass something like `[\"cloche-agent\", \".cloche/workflow.cloche\", \"--resume-from\", \"step-name\"]` directly. The flow becomes much cleaner: commit the old container to create a temp image, then call `Start` with that image and the resume command.\n\nTo make this work, I need to add a `Commit` method to the container runtime interface as an optional capability, similar to how `ImageEnsurer` works. The server can check if the runtime implements it before attempting to use it.\n\nDefining the interface...\n\nNow I'm implementing the Docker runtime's commit functionality to create a tagged image from a container, then adding a `SetPreloadedResults` method to the engine so it can skip already-completed steps by returning cached results instead of re-executing them. The prompt adapter also needs to handle resume mode to pass this information through the workflow.\n\nFor the agent and host runners, I'm adding resume support that preserves previous step outputs, loads completed results, and sets flags to tell the engine and adapter to skip re-execution and continue the conversation from where it left off.\n\nThe gRPC server needs to handle resume requests differently for container and host runs—for containers, it commits the current state and starts a new one with the resume command, while for host runs it just reruns the workflow with resume parameters.\n\nI'm also adding a CLI command to parse resume arguments and trigger the workflow, plus tests to verify the engine, adapter, and CLI all handle resumption correctly. Now I need to figure out how the agent runner determines which steps completed when resuming—it'll check the .cloche/output/ directory to see what's already been executed.\n\nLooking at the protocol module, there's a history file that tracks step results, so I can use that to reconstruct what's already been done.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8152,"cache_read_input_tokens":121820,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8152},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a767d320-7441-4cfb-80d2-26edf647ec06","uuid":"2bf89101-f7e9-40dd-a88d-da115fcfb106"}
